<!--
  Dubs Performance Analyzer profiling tab for Precision Stockpile Control.

  WHY THE TAB WAS EMPTY: Dubs Performance Analyzer only renders entries it can resolve.
  The previous file had the correct shape but empty <Types>/<Methods>/<NestedTypes>, so the
  parser created zero profilers and nothing appeared in-game. The fix is to populate them.

  SCHEMA (per github.com/Dubwise56/Dubs-Performance-Analyzer#using-the-analyzerxml):
    <Analyzer> -> one child = the tab name -> <Types> / <Methods> / <NestedTypes>, each a list of <li>.
    * Types       : fully-qualified type name. Profiles EVERY method declared in that type.
    * Methods     : a single method as Namespace.Class:MethodName. The id carries NO signature,
                    so it is only safe when the name has exactly ONE overload on the declaring type.
    * NestedTypes : profiles methods of the nested types of the named type (for nested patch classes).

  WHAT IS LISTED: the hot paths only. Everything that runs on the per-haul-scan, per-storage-event,
  per-tick, or per-frame-overlay-draw surfaces (see docs/DESIGN.md Performance Rules). Each entry is a
  PSC type that actually has methods. Profiling a patch class shows PSC's OWN added cost on a seam; the
  two <Methods> below are the underlying vanilla methods PSC modifies, profiled to show TOTAL path cost.

  DELIBERATELY OMITTED: warm types (save/load, migration, storage-group + feeder lifecycle, gizmo and
  storage-tab construction) and cold UI (dialogs, menus, sliders, paint designators, clipboard, theme,
  widget helpers). They don't run on hauling/tick hot paths, and profiling them adds overhead and noise.
  Pure enums and method-less structs are omitted too (no methods for the profiler to wrap). To profile a
  warm/cold type, just add its fully-qualified name to <Types>.

  Dev-only file: kept in the GitHub repo, but exclude it from the Steam Workshop upload (the profiling
  tab shouldn't appear for Workshop players).

  Keep comments OUTSIDE the <Analyzer> root. Dubs Performance Analyzer iterates the root's descendant
  nodes as type/method names and can crash on a comment node placed among them.
-->
<Analyzer>
    <PrecisionStockpileControl>
        <Types>
